steps.text:
Confirmed: it is a real `@apply` bug in this revision. The generated stylesheet relies on source order across two separate `.border-dotted` rules, but `@apply` gathers declarations utility-by-utility and loses that ordering.

Yes — this is a bug in this early Tailwind version’s `@apply` implementation.

The normal utility stylesheet relies on rule order:

```css
.border-dotted { border-width: 0; } /* reset, early */
.border { border: 1px solid ...; }  /* width restored */
.border-dotted { border-style: dotted; } /* style, late */
```

So `class="border border-dotted"` works. But `@apply` collects each named utility independently, producing:

```css
.example {
  border: 1px solid ...;
  border-width: 0;
  border-style: dotted;
}
```

The reset now comes after the border shorthand, so it removes the width.

`borderStylesReset` was intentionally added for normal class composition, but splitting one utility across separate generated rules makes it incompatible with how [`findMixin`](/testbed/src/util/findMixin.js:3) expands `@apply`.

Workaround in that version:

```css
.example {
  @apply border-dotted;
  border-width: 1px;
}
```

(or define the complete border declaration yourself). The proper fix is to make `@apply` preserve generated stylesheet order across all matched rules, rather than expanding one requested class at a time.
